post_text:
Congratulations to the following District 303 students for being named semifinalists in the 66th annual National Merit Scholarship Program.
St. Charles East students: Shae Atkins, Henry Nunns and Aidan Szuch.
St. Charles North students: Brett Barnes, Ryan Forester, Nathan Hanselman, Grace Lucchesi, Anastasia Smith-Becker, and Riley Trendler.

These academically talented high school seniors have an opportunity to
continue in the competition for 7,600 National Merit Scholarships worth more than $30 million that will be offered in the spring of 2021. There are approximately 16,000 Semifinalists this year.

post_text: Dr. Robert Allison, Wild Rose principal, was planning to retire at the end of the school year when he passed away in November. Dr. Allison was a bright spot in our district for more than 21 years, having served as principal at both Norton Creek and Wild Rose Elementary Schools, and Director of Instruction and Assistant Superintendent in the District office. He was a positive presence whose dedication to the students, staff members, and parents at Wild Rose and across the district will be sorely missed.
text: Dr. Robert Allison, Wild Rose principal, was planning to retire at the end of the school year when he passed away in November. Dr. Allison was a bright spot in our district for more than 21 years, having served as principal at both Norton Creek and Wild Rose Elementary Schools, and Director of Instruction and Assistant Superintendent in the District office. He was a positive presence whose dedication to the students, staff members, and parents at Wild Rose and across the district will be sorely missed.

text:

post_text: District 303 is partnering with Bernie's Book Bank to provide summer reading materials for families. Each bag, that will be distributed during grab-and-go meal service on June 1, will include a selection of books for students in 1st through 6th grades. Any family may receive a bag of books at Anderson Elementary School or Thompson Middle School between 9:00 a.m. and 11:00 a.m. (until bags are gone).

post_text:
This afternoon, we have made the decision to cancel classes for students on Monday, March 16 and hold an Institute Day for staff. This will allow staff members the time to work on plans for classes that can be delivered remotely. Beginning on Tuesday, March 17, the district buildings will be closed to students through the end of Spring Break. All school activities are also cancelled.

At this time, we will use eLearning days beginning March 17 through March 27. Spring Break will still be observed March 30 through April 3. The tentative return date for on-campus classes is April 6.

Parents received an email message this afternoon.

The message is on the front page of our website district.d303.org. Scroll down to the button labeled An Important Message about District 303 school closings.

post_text:
Richmond students in Mrs. Navis‚Äô science class have been learning about energy conversion and transfer. To put their knowledge to the test, they were challenged to create a system that would convert energy from one form to another to meet a human need or want.
In this case, they had to move food from a truck to a food pantry using a conveyor belt powered by at least two types of energy, such as wind or chemical energy. Using Makey Makey kits, they controlled their computer designs and shared them with the class.

post_text: Wredling Middle School 6th graders in Mrs. Rodriguez's Social Studies class have been studying ancient civilizations and the impact geography has on them. To better understand the significance of the Nile River in Ancient Egypt, they worked together to transform a regular 2D map into a 3D map of the Nile using a variety of materials such as legos, clay, sand, and even edible ingredients to make the landscape as realistic as possible. #D303Learns

post_text: Important message for parents from the St. Charles Fire Department.
shared_text:
City of St. Charles, Illinois Government
January 27 at 4:07 PM ¬∑

Parents, please talk to your children about the dangers of the ‚ÄúOutlet Challenge‚Äù that has gone viral on the TikTok social media app. The challenge calls for inserting a phone-charger partly in an outlet and then touching a coin to the exposed prongs to produce a spark. The result can cause electrical system damage, fire, and potentially serious injuries. Look for scorched outlets in your home, and be sure to talk to your children to let them know if they do this they are putting themselves and others in a dangerous situation.
Thank you helping us keep our community safe.
Acting Fire Chief Scott Swanson
